############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML The number [`\sqrt{2}`] [_]{$rational}{5} rational.
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION If [`\sqrt{2}`] were rational, then [`\sqrt{2}=\frac{p}{q}\text{,}`] with [`p`] and [`q`] coprime. But then [`2q^2=p^2\text{.}`] By [@htmlLink("https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_arithmetic#Canonical_representation_of_a_positive_integer","the Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic","TARGET='_blank'")@]*, the power of [`2`] dividing the left side is odd, while the power of [`2`] dividing the right side is even. This is a contradiction, so [`\sqrt{2}`] [$rational] rational.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
